  footnotes: []
english:
  title: In Response to Geukgi's Poem Sent to Our Elder Brother at Godang
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I follow the mist and fog for a moment into that misty void,
    Where water hollows and wind-carved rocks fill ten thousand gorges.
    At the pagoda's edge near Heerang, a crow pecks the bronze bell,
    Above Goun's tower, a crane dances among the pines.
    I have already let the dust of footsteps wander the secluded path,
    Yet always the immortal's wind descends through half the sky.
    But I smile at what's to come—when you keep watch in your post—
    May the mountain gate's solitary walk be shared as one with me.
  footnotes:
    - Heerang (希朗) refers to a sacred site or temple in Korean Buddhist geography.
    - Goun (孤雲) is a reference to Choe Chi-won (崔致遠), a renowned Silla scholar and poet, whose tower or dwelling place represents a space of scholarly retreat.
    - The 'immortal's wind' (仙飈) evokes the Daoist imagery of transcendence and spiritual freedom that pervades classical East Asian poetry.
    - The poem appears to address a kinsman who may be taking on an administrative or guardianship role ('keeping watch in your post'), with the speaker expressing hope for spiritual companionship despite separation.
